<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-07-31T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-07-31T05:00:00-05:00" n="152" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d152">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/148:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-07-31T11:00:00+01:00">July 31, 1929—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received July 31—9:40 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>139. Embassy’s telegram 137, July 30, 11 a.m.<note n="36" xml:id="d152fn36">Not printed.</note> By an official communiqué
                            published in the newspapers of this morning, local Soviet Embassy
                            reiterates earlier denials of direct negotiations with the Chinese
                            Minister here and denies in particular latest reports stated to come
                            from Washington that the Soviet Embassy has “sounded” Chinese Legation
                            in Berlin in connection with the railway conflict.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>